segments.text: If we would, at the beginning, Mr. Davis, tell us something about your early life, including the names of your parents, the dates and places of their birth and death.
You know, I don't know.
Well, my dad was born in North Alabama, and my mother, I believe, came from Mississippi.
My mother died in 1918.
My dad and I died about 63.
I guess I know it.
Okay, and where were you born then?
I was really born at McGregor, just west of Waco there in 1900.
And where did you move to after that?
We moved to La Mesa in 1906, February 1906.
At that time, there were five children in the family.
We moved in a room with my uncle.
who was living east of La Mesa on a farm in a half dugout.
So they was, and he had five children in his family, so there's 14 of us that stayed in that one-room half dugout for several months.
How did you make that move?
We made the move by coming out of what we called the immigrant car to Big Springs.
from McGregor to Big Springs, and then of course we came in a covered wagon or freight wagon from Big Springs to La Mesa.
And the immigrant car was on the train?
Yes.
Which would that have been?
Texas and Pacific.
And so did you attend schools then in La Mesa?
No, I attended school.
In fact, the first year that we went out here in 1906, there were no schools, no rural schools at all.
It was long about 1978.
They put a one-room school out called the Key School.
It was on Jim Key's land, so it was called the Key School.
The only school east of La Mesa.
So we kids attended a one-room school there for some years.
Later we moved to the McCarty community, which was a little near La Mesa.
But we didn't go to La Mesa.
We had our country, our rural schools.
And did you go there for how many years?
Well, I went there.
The trouble is, we had to work for a living.
You know, I didn't know you'd go to school at Christmas until I was 21 years old.
And I'd come up to Lubbock and stay with my uncle, and I had to do that, you know, because I was busy at home.
There got to be ten of us children in the family, compared to small farmers.
I limped to that, so we children had to work.
So after the crops were all in, then you could go to school?
Then we'd go to school, which would usually be after Christmas.
And then you'd go until what time then in the spring?
Well, we'd go until about April or May in the spring.
Then you'd go back to the farm?
We'd go to the farm.
We was out there planting cotton, hoeing cotton, chopping cotton.
What were your principal crops on your farm then?
Cotton and corn to start with.
But we found out that the dry summers was not good for growing corn.
That's when I first became acquainted with the A&M services.
They introduced milo, or maize as we called it.
Then it would stand a drought and still make grain.
Then pretty soon after that, the Experiment Station here at Lubbock introduced Sudan grass, which was a good grass for cattle and all, when the grass out on the pastures would dry up.
So that was my first introduction to Texas A&M, took to the Experiment Station, and I would say, without any question at all, it turned this country out here
from an in-and-out farming country to a continuous farming country because we could depend on that maize to make, and that would feed our horses and our mules.
It was all done by horsepower.
By in-and-out, you mean people coming in and moving out because they failed?
They dried out, and they had no feed to feed their horses.
They would move downstate.
and so forth, we stayed with it.
But we'd just come and go.
In fact, where we lived out east of Mesa, about 10 or 12 miles, we lived right at the crossroad on the north and south traffic.
And the east and west is just wagon roads.
And you could see wagons any time that you wanted to look out.
And generally, on the dry years, they were going east.
On the better years, they were coming west.
But then after the introduction of sorghum or Milo maize, there was less of this in and out and more of a steady same people staying here.
That's right.
People began to be able to each year growing up grain to feed their horses and cattle.
So the grain then became the subsistence crop and the cotton the money crop?
That's right.
You then finished high school at Lubbock, did you?
I finished high school at Lubbock in 23.
I spent two years, junior and senior year.
What activities were you involved in there that were, say, of an agricultural nature?
Well, I belonged to the vocational agriculture class here, but Mr. Ray Mowery, who had just finished A&M, came out here in 21.
Incidentally, he was the first vocational agriculture teacher on the South Plains in 21.
So through a two-year study and work with Mr. Mowery,
Well, we members of his class, I believe there's five of us, went to A&M in the fall of 23.
Had you had some experience, say, in the 4-H club?
Yes, about 1919, I believe it was.
I was a member of the 4-H club in Dawson County.
Mr. C.T.
Watson was a county agent.
Incidentally, I don't think Mr. Watson had.
He was a graduate of an agricultural school, but he was a good county agent.
And I was in the pig club, and I was in the cotton club, and I was in the milo club.
By having something of my own, it really developed an interest on my part in agriculture.
Through the county agent and the experiment station and your vocational agricultural teacher, you had some prior knowledge of Texas A&M by the time you graduated from Lubbock High School.
That's right.
And this was a basic basis for your deciding to go to school there.
Yes, sir.
There was no question, and I had about four classmates who went with me.
Uh-huh.
Did you go through any type of special procedures to be admitted to A&M?
Not that I recall.
We were just admitted down there.
No problem to it at all.
They just looked at your high school record or whatever took with us, you know.
And nothing to tell.
Of course, there were no scholarships then, to my knowledge or whatnot.
Coming from a very poor family, I worked my way through A&M.
So I milked cows down there.
I was down at A&M there, four years.
You milked cows for four years?
Yes, sir.
Well, I noticed you were in a dairy husbandry major, so were you working in the dairy barns then?
That's the reason I majored in dairy husbandry, because I could get a job milking cows and delivering milk.
I delivered milk to the mess hall, and I would always leave a jug of milk
at the President's home, which was Dr. Bazell's at that time.
On my way to the mess hall, I would leave a can of milk there on Dr. Bazell's back porch.
Did you deliver milk to any of the other professors?
No.
But now I did milk the cows some for Dean Kyle.
Dean was a bad coach at the time.
He had a cow he kept in his yard.
Was that a fairly common practice that the faculty members who lived on campus had to cow?
They either had a cow or they had a garden or whatnot.
I know I worked in the garden for Professor Stangle, who later became Dean Stangle out here.
I kept up his garden as side work.
Do you have any recollection of what you were paid per hour or per week?
Yes, sir.
I remember very well.
Twenty-five cents an hour.
This was for milking and delivering milk?
Working in the gardens and whatever you did.
That was standard wages then?
One, five, six hours.
But you know, I could go to school then, including everything, for just a little over $30 a month.
And you could make that much then, I take it?
Yes, I could.
I did.
I didn't get any help.
What was your first reaction to the school when you arrived there?
Well, it was good, but the freshman came down a few days early.
So we were having a freshman party in the Land of the Hood rebuilding, the show building there, Texas A&M.
And the sophomores run in on us about dark and said, air out.
We didn't know what that was, but they were swinging belts.
paddles, so we hired out there and steered to death.
I'll never forget that I run right down to the railroad track just behind where Kyle Field was there then.
Well, I run off into the water there that was up to my waist, but I got out of it and kept running.
Ended up down there in a farmhouse in the chicken house of a farmer.
And I stayed there probably till 2 or 3 o'clock in the morning.
I decided I'd go back to campus.
But you know, if I'd had the money to pull a ticket home, I'd left there.
But then they got back to campus.
Well, the sophomore said, well, where you been?
We didn't know anything about this.
They kid me.
So after that, I never was freed of it.
Was there anybody there at the station?
to meet you when you got to town or to the campus?
They could have been, but I don't remember that they had been in by there.
It was just about a walk, about a quarter mile to a half mile walk from the station down to the main building, and we found our way down there.
I don't recall.
It could have been, but I don't remember.
How did you receive the assignment to your military company when you...
Frankly, I don't know that either.
All I know is I was placed in Company H infantry, and I don't know that that had been recommended to me or not.
I don't know how I got to that.
I had no knowledge of it.
I know Ray Mowry was in the cadet corps.
It was like you had to be almost then.
That's a tale I'll say here and probably later.
To me, it was one of the best parts of my college training,
I wouldn't give a dime for a military career, but it was just excellent.
But I don't know.
I signed a couple of dates.
And incidentally, my classmates from Lubbock were, too.
And our first year was in Bazell Hall.
And four of us roomed in one room there in Bazell Hall.
That room then was probably designed for two, wasn't it?
It was designed for two.
And of course, after a good many freshmen bumped out or went home.
Well, it was cut down to two.
I presume there were some who had the money to buy a ticket home after that first airing out.
Well, we didn't lose many on that, but I was scared to death.
You know what they called me, and I told them I stayed out there in that chicken house.
They called me Chicken House Davis.
How long did that nickname stay with you?
Oh, I'll never forget it.
But just as soon as it got back to me,
dormitory and saw that the sophomores were good boys, you know, and everything.
Now they'd come in every once in a while, you know, make us bend over under the bed, hit us a time or two with their bells, but it was good boys.
Just sort of let you know they were still there.
That's right.
And I believe in it still.
What do they call it?
I don't know what that is, but it'll come to mind after a while.
But anyway, I think it was very good in its time.
Well, hazing is the term that's commonly referred to that punishment of that charge.
It was one of the best courses we had there.
And of course, when we became sophomores, well, we took care of the freshmen and taught them how to be a man.
Would you describe a typical day
while you were in school?
Well, my day was a little bit different from some.
One thing to say, we all lived along Military Walk, and we marched to our meals every day of the week, including Sunday, and of course we marched to Gwine Hall on Sunday for the services there.
But I would generally, as I say, I worked in the dairy down there,
I would deliver milk in the morning.
So I would go back.
But the day down there to me was all of us were dressed as we should be.
And we always had on a black necktie.
And whenever you met anybody, if you didn't know them, you stuck out your hand or introduced yourself.
I'm Freshman Davis.
And if you didn't know them, and if you met an officer, you would salute him.
And those things were good.
They were very, very good.
I just wish we had them today.
But go to classes.
Enjoy the classes thoroughly.
And we would, generally, you'd have revelry, you know.
And you had to have your lights out by a certain time before midnight.
So we just pretty well stayed in our rooms the whole night.
And since you had the job at the dairy barn, did you have to get up early and then milk the cows before breakfast?
Yes, I did.
I did.
And did you have to report back to the dorm at Reveille?
No.
No, the Reveille was by night, wasn't it?
Was it morning?
Well, morning was usually Reveille.
Morning Reveille, that's right.
Anyway, yeah, we'd have taps by night.
We'd have it both ways.
But anyway, I...
would carry the meal down to the mess hall and I would eat in the kitchen.
But at noon, at dinner, lunch and dinner, I marched with the company down Military Walk.
There was not a whole lot.
Now we had the YMCA there then.
We called it the Y, you know.
do most anything there that read or study or visit or whatnot.
You'd buy soft drinks there in the first floor of it.
And was the swimming pool in there when you were there?
No, the swimming pool, to my knowledge, was not there.
Was there any place at all that you could swim if you were so inclined?
Well, the only place I'd know would be Sealaw and go up to Browse River.
You hiked down to the Brazos and take a swim, huh?
Yeah, I hiked down to the Brazos and take a swim.
Okay.
Because we had our showers there.
I believe you said you lived in Bazell.
First year.
First year.
Where else did you live?
Well, let's see.
Bazell Hall and the dormitory right next to it.
Goodwin?
Goodwin, I believe.
But the last year I was there, I was in Austin Hall, which is a two-story, one of the oldest.
That's one of the old ones.
That one probably didn't have central heat then, did it?
Oh, no.
We carried wood and water.
Did you have a freshman to carry the wood and the water for you?
Yes, sir.
You bet.
But as a freshman living in Bazell, you didn't have to do that then, did you?
No, I don't believe we did.
I believe some of the boys who lived in the older dorms had to.
How was the life in the dormitories?
I imagine it varied from building to building.
Probably so, but I would say, generally speaking, it was quiet.
We were down there to get an education.
In those days, you know, you couldn't have a car on the campus.
You would be automatically expelled if you owned a car.
So the few that had them kept them very carefully hid over in Bryant.
But very few people could own one.
It had no parking problem.
It had no parking lots.
And another thing, you couldn't leave campus except on a court trip unless you got special permission.
You just couldn't get in your car and drive to Houston or Dallas.
We was there and we had our Sunday program just like we had our everyday class program.
And you say your Sunday program, what would your Sunday program consist of?
Well, generally about 9, 30, or 10 o'clock, we would march down to Gwine Hall.
And they would have a special sermon there for us.
They'd get visiting pastors and people to come in.
There would be some singing.
I never did participate in any choir.
But it was just like going to a church service here normally.
But we all went to the same church.
We marched down there, and we marched out.
Did you have anything else on Sunday to occupy your time other than studying?
I don't remember anything.
I said occasionally we'd go down to Bryan's.
I'll have to tell you one story about a trip down there pretty early in my freshman year.
We went down there to Bryan's River, you know.
We'd never been down there before.
In fact, to come to this country, we just didn't have running rivers.
We got real thirsty.
We saw a house there and went up and asked if we could have a drink of water.
We had a sister, you know, or a well with a bucket.
Said we could and it was the home of a colored family.
So me and my classmates or roommates
We'd had a drink of water, you know, so I asked the man what his name was.
He said his name was Davis.
So I got quite a bit of river down there.
My kinfolk's living down there in the Brazos Bottoms.
I didn't even know about it.
So you'd go down to the Brazos River for an occasional swim.
That's right.
And go into Bryan occasionally.
Yes, go in.
We went in on the trolley, you know.
That's the only way you get in there.
Being short of money, I didn't go in for picture shows.
But that would be one of the things that students would go into Bryan for, the picture shows.
We didn't have it on the campus when I was there.
Now later they did, but in my time there.
Did you have any much in the way of visiting lecturers to come in and speak about anything in particular?
Not that I recall.
Did you have any of the classes put on plays or anything of that nature for recreation?
No, they could have, but at least I wasn't a part of it.
And mind you, I didn't have what you might call a fool out there, because I worked part-time.
But I don't recall that, and I was pretty active in the Lubbock High School in plays.
But down there, well, I just happened to be there, and

and the cadet corps I'd say repeatedly there's nothing I enjoyed anymore and I thought contributed more to my education than the cadet corps did but I was a first lieutenant but now my roommate or McCoy was captain of the company but it and I still have my sword or saber in there that 27 but uh
We had a good life.
Mine was a busy life, working my way through, and I was always stood up well in the classes and so forth.
Today we generally think of students who work part-time working a maximum of 20 hours a week.
About how much time did you put in in work, if you can remember?
It probably wouldn't be a whole lot more than that, some more.
But I tell you what, I've had to go down to the dairy barn again many evenings after dark and milk cows, because we'd have them on three times milking them.
And I walked back to the dairy barn, which is just across the tracks there.
We didn't have any pavement there or drainage.
I stepped in those water holes.
I remember them very distinctly.
Yeah, I can imagine.
It was probably not much in the way of outdoor lighting either, was there?
No, very little or no lighting.
But that time, I want to go back to Cadet Corps if you don't mind.
Okay.
That was, in those days, we had a horse cavalry.
We had a horse artillery.
And their barns, too, was across the tracks, not too far from the dairy barn.
I didn't help take care of them.
But at finished times,
And then that was pretty soon after World War I, and A&M had contributed more officers, I believe, to World War I than any other school had, including West Point.
I thoroughly enjoyed our military and our parades out there.
What was the food like in the mess hall?
Well, of course, it was good to me, but the common name down there for any kind of meat was bull neck.
And the common name for any kind of dessert was kush.
So I would say general was good.
Of course, the students served us food.
I never did work in the mess hall except deliver milk.
The students would bring our plates to us.
And I'd say we was well fed on a variety of foods and on a good diet.
While you would hear complaints and all, but as a whole it was nutritional and well balanced and so forth, so I don't think there's any complaints.
Complaints were probably more because of the lack of variety than...
Well, probably so, but I think people would complain anyway, regardless of what they had.
But I think it was good.
Generally, you had your breakfast in the kitchen, though, I believe.
I generally did, because I would bring the milk in the back door, and the cook would fix me a plate, and I'd sit over there.
Incidentally, I'd sit at a table that wasn't too far from the football clubs.
They had their tables back there.
I think they would get a little better breakfast than I would, but the cook took care of me.
Well, it's always good to have a friend in the cook, I would say.
Did the upperclassmen have certain privileges that were denied to the freshmen?
Well, not a whole lot that I recall.
Of course, we had this hazing, which we mentioned.
And there's no question of what the freshmen had to recognize in upperclassmen, particularly sophomores.
But as a whole, I would say that it was a very cooperative and congenial group.
And frankly, I didn't miss anything as a freshman or a sophomore that somebody else had.
If he had more, I didn't know him.
So our officers would eat right at the same table with us.
But I presume it probably was a little easier for a sophomore or a junior to get off campus than it was for a freshman.
Well, it could have been, but not very much.
It's pretty tight on all of them.
Those days and times, you just couldn't run off the date.
Maybe could you have a date down there?
We've talked a little bit about, say, entertainment and recreation.
Are there, such as swimming and going down to Bryan for the movies, and a few things you could do at the Y, presumably games of dominoes or cards of some sort, or were cards allowed?
Well, if there were, I never did see any.
You sure had to keep them hid.
There's no question now about what.
We were not taken care of on an entertainment level.
then that you would be today.
But frankly, I didn't miss it because I hadn't been used to it and so forth.
But there's just no question at all about this difference today.
Well, there certainly are lots of opportunities for entertainment and recreation today.
What would the students say?
You could have a radio and a television today, but we didn't have anything.
You couldn't even have a radio.
No, we didn't have a radio.
They didn't even know what they were.
Did the cadet officers enjoy any special privileges that were not available to the normal cadets?
I don't think so.
I know as I became a senior and a first lieutenant, I don't remember having any particular privileges which I didn't have and sort of fit in.
As we come along,
I came up on Dairy 100.
We had our judging team, went to Chicago, went to Detroit, and went to different dairy shows and judging contests and so forth.
But that was not in my senior year.
That was back in my sophomore or junior year.
One person I talked to mentioned that the company commanders, the captains, each had a pass to the theater in Bryan.
If you did, I didn't know it.
Well, you weren't a company commander.
My roommate, I believe, would have told me about it if he ever had my room.
Well, that might not have been a regular thing.
If you did, I didn't know.
Did you have any favorite instructors?
Well, no, I tell you, actually, I enjoyed all my instructors.
I would have to say a dear hundred that Professor Darnell, I thought, was the strongest, the late Darnell, who died a few years ago.
But these two men and their statements I'll always remember.
One was the dean of agriculture, and incidentally, I believe he taught some classes.
He also had been dean.
One statement he made was,
He said, remember this, if you always work hard enough and wait long enough, you'll come out all right.
And that's been true all along.
The other statement was made by Dr. Virgil P. Lee, who was in economics class.
He said this, he said, sure, we need, not we need management, we need capital, those things, but remember the most important thing is people.
That has meant a lot to me since then, too.
Those are the two statements
that I recall mostly when I was down there.
Of course, I not only took care of Dean Stangle's yard while he was there and he came out here, but I enjoyed him as a teacher and others down there.
The dean you mentioned would have been Dean Kyle.
Dean Kyle, yes, Dean Kyle.
